{'completion_tokens': 11993, 'response': Response_structure(reasoning='Below is a concise outline of how one can arrive at an 8\u202fKB cluster size and an 8\u202fKB threshold T while meeting the two constraints—namely at most 0.5% fragmentation overhead and at most 0.05% metadata overhead.\n\n1) Metadata overhead requirement:\n   • Each cluster requires 4\u202fbytes (B) of mapping, i.e. 4\u202fB per cluster.\n   • For a 1\u202fTB partition (=1\u202f073\u202f741\u202f824\u202fKB), choosing cluster size c\u202fKB yields (1\u202f073\u202f741\u202f824 / c) clusters.\n   • Thus total metadata in bytes = 4 × (1\u202f073\u202f741\u202f824 / c).\n   • That must not exceed 0.05\u202f% (i.e. 0.0005) of the total partition size in bytes.\n   • The minimum cluster size c that satisfies: 4 × (1\u202f073\u202f741\u202f824 / c) ≤ 0.0005 × (1\u202f073\u202f741\u202f824 × 1024) works out to c ≥ about 8\u202fKB. So c must be at least 8\u202fKB.\n\n2) Fragmentation overhead requirement:\n   • We define the small‑file threshold T\u202fKB. The fraction of files that are ≤\u202fT\u202fKB is P_small(T) = 0.8 × (1 − exp(−T/4.1)).\n   • With cluster size = c\u202fKB, the average wasted space is:\n     – W_small = c − 2 (KB wasted) on each small file (files ≤\u202fT\u202fKB),\n     – W_large = c/2 (KB wasted) on each large file (files >\u202fT\u202fKB).\n   • Hence the overall average wasted space per file = P_small(T) × (c − 2) + (1 − P_small(T)) × (c / 2).\n   • Multiplying by the total number of files (1\u202f000\u202f000) gives total wasted space in KB, which must be ≤ 0.5\u202f% of 1\u202fTB.\n\nBy testing c = 8\u202fKB and T in various ranges, one finds:\n   • c = 8\u202fKB fixes the metadata overhead at exactly 0.05\u202f%.  \n   • For T = 8\u202fKB, the fragmentation overhead ends up right at about 0.50\u202f%.  \n\nHence choosing c = 8\u202fKB and T = 8\u202fKB yields exactly 0.50\u202f% fragmentation overhead and 0.05\u202f% metadata overhead, meeting both design requirements.', c